Data preprocessing

Overview

We preprocess DHIS2 data by cleaning and formatting monthly routine health facility records to generate cleaned datasets at both the facility and administrative levels. These datasets directly support SNT analysis.

Objectives
  • Import and /or combine DHIS2 data files
  • Select and rename key variables
  • Compute new variables and save at health facility level for reporting rate calculation
  • Aggregate data monthly and yearly at the selected administrative level
  • Save and export the aggregated data monthly and yearly at the selected administrative level

Prerequisites:

  • We are using data from Sierra Leone as an example, and it’s available for download here!

  • Extract the contents of the zipped folder and move the unzipped folder to your working directory.

  • To run the code, use one of the following options:

    • RStudio (recommended for local development)

    • Google Colab with an R kernel (great for cloud-based access)

  • Choose the environment that works best for you and get started with your analysis!

Step-by-Step

The code below details the data preprocessing steps required for SNT analysis, with a focus on epidemiological stratification. It does not include outlier detection and correction, which is addressed in the next section. Follow the steps and instructions carefully, paying close attention to the parts of the code marked for modification and those that should remain unchanged. These areas are clearly indicated at the end of the script. Make sure to follow the guidance precisely. Let’s get started!

Step 3: Read files in the working directory

This function retrieves the files from the working directory and converts them into a DataFrame. Ensure that only the DHIS2 downloaded files are present in the working directory when running the code. If there are other Excel files (.xlsx or .xls) or CSV files with the same extension in the DHIS2 folder, it may lead to errors. Be mindful of this when using the function.

  • R
  • Python
Show the code 
read_and_combine_excel_files <- function(directory = "C:/Users/User/snt-code-library/english/data_r", 
                                         pattern = "\\.xls$") {
  tryCatch({
    # Set working directory
    setwd(directory)

    # Find Excel files matching the pattern
    file_paths <- list.files(pattern = pattern, full.names = TRUE)

    # Stop if no files found
    if (length(file_paths) == 0) stop("No Excel files found in the directory.")

    # Read all Excel files
    data_files <- lapply(file_paths, function(file) {
      tryCatch({
        read_excel(file)
      }, error = function(e) {
        NULL
      })
    })

    # Combine all data frames
    combined_df <- bind_rows(data_files)

    # Trim whitespace from column names
    names(combined_df) <- trimws(names(combined_df))

    return(combined_df)
  }, error = function(e) {
    return(NULL)
  })
}

# Call the function
df <- read_and_combine_excel_files()

Step 5: Compute new variables

We are computing variables to derive totals for specific indicators. In the raw dataset, these indicators are disaggregated by age group, community, and health facility level. For example, if we want to calculate the total number of outpatient visits, the DHIS2 raw data does not provide a direct total, but it includes components that can be summed—such as allout_u5 and allout_ov5.

This same logic applies to other indicators like total suspected cases (susp), total tested (test), confirmed cases (conf), treated cases (maltreat), and total presume cases(pres). The code snippet below shows how we compute these total variables using the appropriate components.

For illustration, we are using Sierra Leone’s country malaria dataset. While the code structure remains the same, the specific variable names may differ for other countries, so it’s important to review and update the variable names carefully when adapting the code.

At the end of the code, we have clearly highlighted which parts should be modified and which should remain unchanged. Please follow those instructions strictly to ensure the code can be reused efficiently and without errors.

Now, let’s get started with the code.

  • R
  • Python
Show the code 
create_variables <- function(df) {
 tryCatch({
   # allout
   df$allout <- rowSums(df[c("allout_u5", "allout_ov5")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # susp
   df$susp <- rowSums(df[c("susp_u5_hf", "susp_5_14_hf", "susp_ov15_hf",
                          "susp_u5_com", "susp_5_14_com", "susp_ov15_com")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # test_hf
   test_hf_cols <- c("test_neg_mic_u5_hf", "test_pos_mic_u5_hf", "test_neg_mic_5_14_hf",
                     "test_pos_mic_5_14_hf", "test_neg_mic_ov15_hf", "test_pos_mic_ov15_hf",
                     "tes_neg_rdt_u5_hf", "tes_pos_rdt_u5_hf", "tes_neg_rdt_5_14_hf",
                     "tes_pos_rdt_5_14_hf", "tes_neg_rdt_ov15_hf", "tes_pos_rdt_ov15_hf")
   df$test_hf <- rowSums(df[test_hf_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # test_com
   test_com_cols <- c("tes_neg_rdt_u5_com", "tes_pos_rdt_u5_com", "tes_neg_rdt_5_14_com",
                      "tes_pos_rdt_5_14_com", "tes_neg_rdt_ov15_com", "tes_pos_rdt_ov15_com")
   df$test_com <- rowSums(df[test_com_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # test
   df$test <- rowSums(df[c("test_hf", "test_com")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # conf_hf
   conf_hf_cols <- c("test_pos_mic_u5_hf", "test_pos_mic_5_14_hf", "test_pos_mic_ov15_hf",
                     "tes_pos_rdt_u5_hf", "tes_pos_rdt_5_14_hf", "tes_pos_rdt_ov15_hf")
   df$conf_hf <- rowSums(df[conf_hf_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # conf_com
   conf_com_cols <- c("tes_pos_rdt_u5_com", "tes_pos_rdt_5_14_com", "tes_pos_rdt_ov15_com")
   df$conf_com <- rowSums(df[conf_com_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # conf
   df$conf <- rowSums(df[c("conf_hf", "conf_com")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maltreat_com
   maltreat_com_cols <- c("maltreat_u24_u5_com", "maltreat_ov24_u5_com", "maltreat_u24_5_14_com",
                         "maltreat_ov24_5_14_com", "maltreat_u24_ov15_com", "maltreat_ov24_ov15_com")
   df$maltreat_com <- rowSums(df[maltreat_com_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maltreat_hf
   maltreat_hf_cols <- c("maltreat_u24_u5_hf", "maltreat_ov24_u5_hf", "maltreat_u24_5_14_hf",
                        "maltreat_ov24_5_14_hf", "maltreat_u24_ov15_hf", "maltreat_ov24_ov15_hf")
   df$maltreat_hf <- rowSums(df[maltreat_hf_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maltreat
   df$maltreat <- rowSums(df[c("maltreat_hf", "maltreat_com")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # pres_com
   df$pres_com <- pmax(df$maltreat_com - df$conf_com, 0, na.rm = TRUE)

   # pres_hf
   df$pres_hf <- pmax(df$maltreat_hf - df$conf_hf, 0, na.rm = TRUE)

   # pres
   df$pres <- rowSums(df[c("pres_com", "pres_hf")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maladm
   df$maladm <- rowSums(df[c("maladm_u5", "maladm_5_14", "maladm_ov15")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maldth
   maldth_cols <- c("maldth_u5", "maldth_1_59m", "maldth_10_14", "maldth_5_9",
                    "maldth_5_14", "maldth_ov15", "maldth_fem_ov15", "maldth_mal_ov15")
   df$maldth <- rowSums(df[maldth_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   return(df)
 })
  
}
# Call the function
df <- create_variables(df)

Step 6: Split periodname into month and year

The raw data does not contain separate columns for month and year. Instead, both are combined in a single column called periodname (e.g., “January 2023”). To address this, we are splitting the periodname column to create two new columns: one for month and another for year.

  • R
  • Python
# Define the function
separate_periodname <- function(df, col_name = "periodname") {
  tryCatch({
    
    # Separate the column into 'month' and 'year'
    df <- separate(df, col = all_of(col_name), into = c("month", "year"), sep = " ")
    message("Column separated successfully.")
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("Error: ", conditionMessage(e))
  })
  return(df)
}
# Call the function
df <- separate_periodname(df)

To properly adapt the code:

  • Line 1: Change the periodname in the function above to match the one in your dataset.

  • Copy, paste and run the code into your script

Step 7: Recode month

We are converting the month to a numeric format for easier and cleaner visualization when plotting heatmaps. Specifically, we format the date as “YYYY-MM” (e.g., “2015-09”) instead of using the full month name (e.g., “September 2015”). This shorter format prevents the x-axis from becoming overcrowded, which can cause labels to overlap and display poorly.

  • R
  • Python
#Define the function
recode_months <- function(df) {
  tryCatch({   
    # Recode month names to numbers
    df$month <- recode(df$month,
      "January" = "01",
      "February" = "02",
      "March" = "03",
      "April" = "04",
      "May" = "05",
      "June" = "06",
      "July" = "07",
      "August" = "08",
      "September" = "09",
      "October" = "10",
      "November" = "11",
      "December" = "12"
    )
    
    message("Month names successfully recoded.")
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("Error: ", conditionMessage(e))
  })
  
  return(df)
}

# Call the function
df <- recode_months(df)

Step 8: Create a date column in datetime format

This step create a new date column in the YYYY-MM format to ensure clear and consistent representation when plotting line charts or heatmaps.

  • R
  • Python
# Define the function
create_date_column <- function(df) {
  tryCatch({
    # Check if 'year' and 'month' columns exist
    if (!all(c("year", "month") %in% colnames(df))) {
      stop("Columns 'year' and/or 'month' are missing from the dataframe.")
    }
    # Unite 'year' and 'month' into 'date' column
    df <- df %>%
      unite("date", year, month, sep = "-", remove = FALSE)

    message("Date column successfully created.")
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("Eror: ", conditionMessage(e))
  })

  return(df)
}
# Call the function
df <- create_date_column(df)

Step 9: Save health facility data in xls, xlsx or csv form

We are saving the data at the health facility level because several analyses are specific to health facilities.

# Function to save health facility data to Excel
save_hf_data_to_excel <- function(df, filename) {
  tryCatch({
    # Define the 'output' folder path and create it
    output_folder <- file.path(getwd(), "hf_data_output")
    dir.create(output_folder, recursive = TRUE) # Create the folder
    
    # Build full file path inside 'hf_data_output' folder
    full_path <- file.path(output_folder, filename)
    
    # Save dataframe to Excel
    write_xlsx(df, full_path)
    
    return(invisible(df))  # Return the dataframe invisibly
  }, error = function(e) {
    stop(e)  # Stop if an error occurs
  })
}

# Save the dataframe and assign the result
df <- save_hf_data_to_excel(df, "health_facility_data.xlsx")

Step 10: Group and aggregate monthly data at the adm1/adm2/adm3 level

We are saving the monthly data at the adm1/adm2/adm3 level, as many analyses are specific to these administrative levels. For illustration, we will use adm1 as a case study. However, at the end of the code, clear instructions are provided on how to group and aggregate the data at the adm2 and adm3 levels.

  • R
  • Python
Show the code 
# Define the function
aggregate_monthly_data <- function(df) {
  
  tryCatch({
    # Get current working directory
    current_dir <- getwd()
    
    # Define the 'output' folder path and create it
    output_folder <- file.path(current_dir, "monthly_data_output")
    dir.create(output_folder, recursive = TRUE)  # Create the folder
    
    # Group and aggregate data
    monthly_data <- df %>%
      group_by(adm1, year, month, date) %>%
      summarise(across(where(is.numeric), \(x) sum(x, na.rm = TRUE)), .groups = "drop")
    
    # Write files to the 'montly_data_output' folder
    write_xlsx(monthly_data, file.path(output_folder, "aggregated_data_monthly_adm1_data.xlsx"))
    write_csv(monthly_data, file.path(output_folder, "aggregated_data_monthly_adm1_data.csv"))
    
    # Confirmation message
    message("Files saved to: ", output_folder)
    
    return(monthly_data)
    
  }, error = function(e) {
    # Handle error and print the error message
    message("An error occurred: ", e$message)
    return(NULL)  # Return NULL if error occurs
  })
}

# Call the function with the dataframe
df <- aggregate_monthly_data(df)

Step 11: Group and aggregate yearly data at the adm1/adm2/adm3 level

We are saving the yearly data at the adm1/adm2/adm3 level, as many analyses are specific to these administrative levels. For illustration, we will use adm1 as a case study. However, at the end of the code, clear instructions are provided on how to group and aggregate the data at the adm2 and adm3 levels.

  • Python
Show the code 
# Define the function
aggregate_yearly_data <- function(df) {
  tryCatch({
    # Get current working directory
    current_dir <- getwd()
    
    # Define the 'output' folder path and create it
    output_folder <- file.path(current_dir, "yearly_data_output")
    dir.create(output_folder, recursive = TRUE)  # Create the folder
    
    # Group and aggregate data
    yearly_data <- df %>%
      group_by(adm1, year) %>%
      summarise(across(where(is.numeric), \(x) sum(x, na.rm = TRUE)), .groups = "drop")
    
    # Write files to the 'yearly_data_output' folder
    write_xlsx(yearly_data, file.path(output_folder, "aggregated_data_yearly_adm1_data.xlsx"))
    write_csv(yearly_data, file.path(output_folder, "aggregated_data_yearly_adm1_data.csv"))
    
    # Confirmation message
    message("Files saved to: ", output_folder)
    return(yearly_data)
    
  }, error = function(e) {
    return(NULL)
  })
}

# Call the function with your dataframe
df <- aggregate_yearly_data(df)

# Define the function
read_and_combine_excel_files <- function(directory = "C:/Users/User/snt-code-library/english/data_r", 
                                         pattern = "\\.xls$") {
  tryCatch({
    # Set working directory
    setwd(directory)

    # Find Excel files matching the pattern
    file_paths <- list.files(pattern = pattern, full.names = TRUE)

    # Stop if no files found
    if (length(file_paths) == 0) stop("No Excel files found in the directory.")

    # Read all Excel files
    data_files <- lapply(file_paths, function(file) {
      tryCatch({
        read_excel(file)
      }, error = function(e) {
        NULL
      })
    })

    # Combine all data frames
    combined_df <- bind_rows(data_files)

    # Trim whitespace from column names
    names(combined_df) <- trimws(names(combined_df))

    return(combined_df)
  }, error = function(e) {
    return(NULL)
  })
}

# Call the function
df <- read_and_combine_excel_files()

# Defin ethe function
create_variables <- function(df) {
 tryCatch({
   
   # allout
   df$allout <- rowSums(df[c("allout_u5", "allout_ov5")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # susp
   df$susp <- rowSums(df[c("susp_u5_hf", "susp_5_14_hf", "susp_ov15_hf",
                          "susp_u5_com", "susp_5_14_com", "susp_ov15_com")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # test_hf
   test_hf_cols <- c("test_neg_mic_u5_hf", "test_pos_mic_u5_hf", "test_neg_mic_5_14_hf",
                     "test_pos_mic_5_14_hf", "test_neg_mic_ov15_hf", "test_pos_mic_ov15_hf",
                     "tes_neg_rdt_u5_hf", "tes_pos_rdt_u5_hf", "tes_neg_rdt_5_14_hf",
                     "tes_pos_rdt_5_14_hf", "tes_neg_rdt_ov15_hf", "tes_pos_rdt_ov15_hf")
   df$test_hf <- rowSums(df[test_hf_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # test_com
   test_com_cols <- c("tes_neg_rdt_u5_com", "tes_pos_rdt_u5_com", "tes_neg_rdt_5_14_com",
                      "tes_pos_rdt_5_14_com", "tes_neg_rdt_ov15_com", "tes_pos_rdt_ov15_com")
   df$test_com <- rowSums(df[test_com_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # test
   df$test <- rowSums(df[c("test_hf", "test_com")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # conf_hf
   conf_hf_cols <- c("test_pos_mic_u5_hf", "test_pos_mic_5_14_hf", "test_pos_mic_ov15_hf",
                     "tes_pos_rdt_u5_hf", "tes_pos_rdt_5_14_hf", "tes_pos_rdt_ov15_hf")
   df$conf_hf <- rowSums(df[conf_hf_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # conf_com
   conf_com_cols <- c("tes_pos_rdt_u5_com", "tes_pos_rdt_5_14_com", "tes_pos_rdt_ov15_com")
   df$conf_com <- rowSums(df[conf_com_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # conf
   df$conf <- rowSums(df[c("conf_hf", "conf_com")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maltreat_com
   maltreat_com_cols <- c("maltreat_u24_u5_com", "maltreat_ov24_u5_com", "maltreat_u24_5_14_com",
                         "maltreat_ov24_5_14_com", "maltreat_u24_ov15_com", "maltreat_ov24_ov15_com")
   df$maltreat_com <- rowSums(df[maltreat_com_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maltreat_hf
   maltreat_hf_cols <- c("maltreat_u24_u5_hf", "maltreat_ov24_u5_hf", "maltreat_u24_5_14_hf",
                        "maltreat_ov24_5_14_hf", "maltreat_u24_ov15_hf", "maltreat_ov24_ov15_hf")
   df$maltreat_hf <- rowSums(df[maltreat_hf_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maltreat
   df$maltreat <- rowSums(df[c("maltreat_hf", "maltreat_com")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # pres_com
   df$pres_com <- pmax(df$maltreat_com - df$conf_com, 0, na.rm = TRUE)

   # pres_hf
   df$pres_hf <- pmax(df$maltreat_hf - df$conf_hf, 0, na.rm = TRUE)

   # pres
   df$pres <- rowSums(df[c("pres_com", "pres_hf")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maladm
   df$maladm <- rowSums(df[c("maladm_u5", "maladm_5_14", "maladm_ov15")], na.rm = TRUE)

   # maldth
   maldth_cols <- c("maldth_u5", "maldth_1_59m", "maldth_10_14", "maldth_5_9",
                    "maldth_5_14", "maldth_ov15", "maldth_fem_ov15", "maldth_mal_ov15")
   df$maldth <- rowSums(df[maldth_cols], na.rm = TRUE)

   return(df)
 })
  
}
# Call the function
df <- create_variables(df)

# Define the function
separate_periodname <- function(df, col_name = "periodname") {
  tryCatch({
    
    # Separate the column into 'month' and 'year'
    df <- separate(df, col = all_of(col_name), into = c("month", "year"), sep = " ")
    message("Column separated successfully.")
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("Error: ", conditionMessage(e))
  })
  return(df)
}
# Call the function
df <- separate_periodname(df)

#Define the function
recode_months <- function(df) {
  tryCatch({   
    # Recode month names to numbers
    df$month <- recode(df$month,
      "January" = "01",
      "February" = "02",
      "March" = "03",
      "April" = "04",
      "May" = "05",
      "June" = "06",
      "July" = "07",
      "August" = "08",
      "September" = "09",
      "October" = "10",
      "November" = "11",
      "December" = "12"
    )
    
    message("Month names successfully recoded.")
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("Error: ", conditionMessage(e))
  })
  
  return(df)
}

# Call the function
df <- recode_months(df)


#===============================================================================
# Step 8: create a date column in datetime format
#===============================================================================

# Define the function
create_date_column <- function(df) {
  tryCatch({
    # Check if 'year' and 'month' columns exist
    if (!all(c("year", "month") %in% colnames(df))) {
      stop("Columns 'year' and/or 'month' are missing from the dataframe.")
    }
    # Unite 'year' and 'month' into 'date' column
    df <- df %>%
      unite("date", year, month, sep = "-", remove = FALSE)

    message("Date column successfully created.")
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("Eror: ", conditionMessage(e))
  })

  return(df)
}
# Call the function
df <- create_date_column(df)

# Step 9: create a hf_uid

# Function to create a unique HF ID column, stops on error
create_hfid_column <- function(df) {
  tryCatch({
    df <- df %>%
      group_by(adm1, adm2, adm3, hf) %>%                     # Group by location and HF
      mutate(hf_uid = sprintf("hf_%04d", cur_group_id())) %>% # Create unique ID like hf_0001
      ungroup()                                              # Remove grouping
    return(df)                                               # Return modified dataframe
  }, error = function(e) {
    stop(e)                                                  # Stop and show the error
  })
}

# Apply the function to the dataframe
df <- create_hfid_column(df)
datatable(df, options = list(pageLength = 5, autoWidth = TRUE))

# Define the function
save_hf_data_to_excel <- function(df, filename) {
  tryCatch({
    full_path <- file.path(getwd(), filename)  # Build full file path
    write_xlsx(df, full_path)                  # Save dataframe to Excel
    return(invisible(df))                      # Return the dataframe invisibly
  }, error = function(e) {
    stop(e)                                     # Stop if an error occurs
  })
}
# Save the dataframe and assign the result
result <- save_hf_data_to_excel(df, "health_facility_data.xlsx")

#===============================================================================
# Step 11: group and aggregate monthly data at the adm1 level
#===============================================================================

# Define the function
aggregate_monthly_data <- function(df) {
  
  tryCatch({
    # Get current working directory
    current_dir <- getwd()
    
    # Group and aggregate data
    monthly_data <- df %>%
      group_by(adm1, year, month, date) %>%
      summarise(across(where(is.numeric), \(x) sum(x, na.rm = TRUE)), .groups = "drop")
    
    # Write files to current directory
    write_xlsx(monthly_data, file.path(current_dir, "aggregated_data_monthly_adm1_data.xlsx"))
    write_csv(monthly_data, file.path(current_dir, "aggregated_data_monthly_adm1_data.csv"))
    
    # Confirmation message
    message("Files saved to: ", current_dir)
    
    return(monthly_data)
    
  }, error = function(e) {
    # Handle error and print the error message
    message("An error occurred: ", e$message)
    return(NULL)  # Return NULL if error occurs
  })
}

# Call the function with the dataframe
result <- aggregate_monthly_data(df)
datatable(result, options = list(pageLength = 5, autoWidth = TRUE))
